Here's the full picture, structure plus specific beats plus the worldbuilding we've layered in.

## Overall Structure

**Format:** Novella (25-40 pages), written prose-first with a script adaptation possible later.

**Premise:** David is driving alone at night on an endless, featureless backroad — flat, straight, wooded, no landmarks, no way to gauge time or distance. What begins as ordinary highway hypnosis slowly reveals itself as something else: the radio bleeds wrongness into the world, and David realizes, too late, that he isn't driving — he's being driven. This is his personal hell, built from every wrong turn he ever took.

## Quarter-by-Quarter Beats

**INTRO** — David driving, radio low, totally mundane internal state. A bump snaps him out of highway hypnosis. He mutters "wake up," switches to AM out of boredom.

**QUARTER ONE — Normal Bleeds Into Wrong**
- AM commodities report: real grain prices (drawn from 1984 as a deliberate "if you know, you know" detail) sliding into wrong ones — suet, blood meal, then human flesh, delivered with total flatness.
- Weather report: temperatures far too extreme (140°F), still delivered calmly.
- David does his first real double-take. Starts actively listening/looking around.
- Local news segment: introduces the "small town casually announces something horrifying" beat — currently landing on ticket sales for a fair "skinning," said with the enthusiasm of a raffle announcement.
- (Still open: additional wrongness beats to round out Quarter One before transitioning to Quarter Two.)

**QUARTER TWO — Escalation, Searching for Normal**
- David starts actively scanning/seeking stations instead of using presets.
- Tejano music, Spanish-language talk radio — skipped.
- A station with static underneath: distant screaming, scuffling, industrial machinery sounds.
- Switches to FM — all music stations replaced with wrongness (Mongolian throat singing briefly, then alien/demonic sound on everything). He doesn't notice the moment it all changed.
- Panic rising — muttering to himself, looking around at the unchanging road.
- Back to AM — all static now.
- Finds one station: pristine, silent, no artifacts at all.
- A voice emerges — unnaturally deep, subsonic, wet mouth-sounds, wrong vocal register (think: a mouth structure built for a different kind of speaking entirely).
- Voice: *"Have you been good, David?"*

**QUARTER THREE — What's Real?**
- Obsessive gas gauge and clock checking — clock never agrees with itself, always night, no consistent time passing.
- Radio voices multiply — father, brother, friends, lovers — naming his betrayals, mocking him, "hosting a show about him."
- Glimpses out the window: landscape subtly wrong (uncanny valley before uncanny valley). One glimpse of something massive moving among the trees (giant insect-leg shape) that his brain files as "weird tree."
- Road never curves. Still endless.
- Radio stations start flipping on their own, faster, voices layering into cacophony.
- David tries to rationalize: "This is just highway hypnosis." Evidence keeps contradicting him.

**QUARTER FOUR — The Dawning**
- Wheel jerks under his hands like it's alive. Pedals go dead.
- Realization: he's not driving — something else is.
- This is judgment — a road built from every wrong turn he ever took.
- He's always been on this road. He just stopped pretending he could escape it.
- Red light pulses on the horizon like breathing.
- Voices howl in triumphant laughter.
- Car accelerates toward the waiting inferno.
- Final beat: this was never a road.

## Worldbuilding Layer — "The Nameless Thing"

- Named entities that appear in the story (currently: Albasty, a real Turkic/Central Asian demon tied to nightmares and suffocation) are never explained — just dropped in passing, treated as mundane by whoever's speaking.
- Underlying concept (not stated on the page, purely structural): all these named regional demons across history/folklore are actually fragments — different cultures independently naming the same underlying, bodiless, nameless thing. It predates individual mythology, predates writing, predates even the concept of being a single discrete entity. Real academic grounding: comparative mythology (Julien d'Huy's phylogenetic myth reconstruction) can prove certain monster/myth shapes are 15,000-20,000+ years old — older than any name that survives.
- Rule: any named entity gets mentioned once, in passing, never explained.

## Style Rules Established
- No "just" as filler.
- No triple-listing/repetition (a known AI tell you're actively avoiding).
- No adjective-stacking — one strong image beats three.
- Real, verifiable factual grounding wherever possible (commodity prices, folklore names, historical data) so the "wrongness" lands as authentic rather than invented-sounding.
- Small-town horror delivered with total emotional flatness — the horror is in the mismatch between tone and content, not the content alone.
